# pandoc-nvim-preview: Local Browser-Based Pandoc Writing Workbench

## Goal

- Current defect/state: No existing tool combines a real Neovim instance (with all user plugins, keymaps, LSP) with live Pandoc preview in a browser-based split-pane GUI that is directly testable via Playwright.
- Target state: A `pandoc-nvim-preview` CLI that starts a local web server, opens a browser window with an xterm.js terminal pane (running real nvim) on the left and a live Pandoc-rendered HTML preview on the right, with a Playwright E2E test suite that certifies the real stack end-to-end.
- Why this matters: The architecture is resistant to agent reward-hacking -- tests assert process reality (real nvim process), terminal reality (keystrokes reach nvim), render reality (Pandoc output in DOM), and artifact reality (saved files match buffer). No mock backend can satisfy these checks.

## Constraints

- Required:
  - TypeScript for server and frontend bundling (Node.js -- no Electron, Tauri, Qt, GTK)
  - `node-pty` for PTY spawning (native C++ addon, proven with xterm.js)
  - `@xterm/xterm` + `@xterm/addon-fit` for browser terminal emulation
  - Real `nvim` process (never `--headless` for the PTY instance; `--headless` only for the dedicated RPC-only companion if needed)
  - Pandoc for all rendering (MathJax or KaTeX for math, `--citeproc` for citations)
  - Playwright for all E2E tests (driving the browser against the production runtime)
  - All runtime state lives in the Neovim buffer -- save/export always queries the live buffer first
- Forbidden:
  - Mock backends, headless-only nvim for the terminal pane, or test-only code paths
  - Electron/Tauri wrapping in initial implementation (defer to later phase)
  - Tight coupling between terminal rendering and preview rendering
  - Stale buffer caching that could serve content not matching the Neovim buffer
- Approval gates:
  - Plan must be approved before any implementation begins
  - All Playwright tests must pass against the production runtime before declaring any phase complete

